views.text: peacegate  Article 06-Aug-2023 Dawn of Mediation – A relief for Justice? The Rajya Sabha has passed the Mediation Act on 1st August 2023. Even though the Mediation Act has its drawbacks, it could be considered as the first step to bring in a culture of amicable dispute resolution which could be initiated by parties before attempting adjudicatory dispute resolution methods. That should make all of us happy, considering the huge delay in access to justice. The article analyses the pros and cons of the new Mediation Act. Read More

peacegate  Article 20-Jun-2023 Call for Peace and Development by Global Youth The Youth bear the brunt of contemporary challenges faced by the world such as rising conflicts, inequality, environmental degradation, public health deterioration, loss of livelihoods and unemployment. The global youth is about to create history by telling the World leaders that they do not want war, conflicts, intolerance and tensions and that they want Peace in Action, justice and sustainable development, as they believe that peace and harmony is the only way humanity and world can survive and co-exist peacefully. During the G20 Presidency of the Government of India hosting the G20 leaders at New Delhi, India, as an expression of solidarity with the G20 nations and the United Nations to implement to the Sustainable Development Goals (SDGs) of the UN focusing on Peace, Justice and Strong Institutions, the global youth is making a pledge to support peace. Along with the Pledge, a representative section of the global youth will assemble for the International Peace20 Youth Summit at Kochi, India during August 2023 as a Global Youth Movement for World Peace and Sustainable Development. This is conceived as a convening platform for youth to experience and channel peace, celebrate life in all its diversity and co-create livelihood opportunities to sustain life and wellbeing for people and the planet. This will also provide increased interaction and collaboration between the United Nations 2030 Agenda’s Sustainable Development Goals and the Youth. There is increasing acknowledgement that such initiatives, in addition to instilling hope in the Youth, help hone their capacities for civic engagement thereby becoming active citizens. In this context, the civil society needs to play a more proactive role in galvanizing the Youth to work for a hopeful, peaceful and creative future. The Sustainable Development Goals of the United Nations Agenda 2030 is one such platform that can instil hope for the future, harnessing the creative potential of the Youth and their innate motivation to do good. As per the Peace Pledge, the youth declare their commitment to promote civility, peaceful co-existence and harmony in the society. The Pledge is as follows: 1. We understand that even though there are many different ethnicities, languages, customs and beliefs in the world, we are all members of the one human race and as such our differences are a core aspect of humankind. 2. We understand that whatever be our differences and whatever conflicts we face, we could resolve it amicably and we will empower ourselves to resolve such disputes in a consensual manner, preserving the relationship among people and peace in the community. 3. We understand that Peace will co-exist only with sustainable development, environment harmony, individual liberty and compassion towards all species. We, humans, share our planet earth with plants and animals and we have no right to infringe on the livelihood of any other species and understanding of nature obliges us to maintain the integrity of the environment, so that it can contribute to a healthy planet. 4. Therefore, we promise that, should any strife or dispute arise in our life, we will try to manage it amicably and peacefully as the first step to resolve such issue and we understand that such a culture could lay the foundation to a long term process of positive social transition by making the society just, equal and fair and will instill a commitment to peace and faith in humanity and nature and will work forward towards contributing to the acceleration of UN Agenda on Sustainable Development Goals. After the International Peace20 Youth Summit, the global youth, with the assistance of former UN officials, would place these Pledge documents to the G20 Leaders and the UN Secretary General, informing their desire to strive for Peace and Sustainable Development in compliance with SDG 16 and 17 of the UN. The International Peace20 Youth Summit had its inception in Indonesia in 2022. Prior to the G20 Leaders meeting in Bali, Indonesia, the Youth and Civil Society met at Bali on November 1-2, 2022, where they organized the Youth Summit to promote a culture of peace, harmony, and sustainable development amongst the Youth. The Summit was organized through the patronage of Prince Dr. Damien Dematra, Princess Natasha Dematra and Princess Cheryl Halpern. An outcome of the Summit was the “Peace Pledge” taken by all participants, where about 23,000 signatures were collected from all over the world, announcing their support to G20 Indonesia and a call for making a pathway for a Fair and Better World for future generations. Building on the legacy of the IP20 Youth Summit in Bali, a similar summit is planned at Kochi, India on 11-12 August 2023, India a month prior to the official meeting of G20 Leaders in India during September 2023. The International Peace20 Youth Summit Kochi will be a Civil Society initiative for, of and by the Youth to promote peace and sustainable development, locally and globally, and call on the G20 Leaders to advance peace, end conflicts and promote sustainable development. It is understood that to make a pathway for a fair and better world for the future generation, peace and development must go hand-in-hand. Without Peace there is no Development and Without Development there is no Peace. The Peace Pledge can be signed online using the Peacegate application (www.peacegate.in). This cause for maintaining peace and harmony for peaceful co-existence is supported by the Indian Institute of Arbitration & Mediation (www.arbitrationindia.com). If you are between the age group of 15-32 and would like to participate in this global youth movement and would like to sign the pledge, please sign the Peace Pledge at https://peacegate.in/ip20ys-pledge For more details about the International Peace20 Youth Summit, please visit www.ip20ysindia.in We invite you to be part of this revolutionto create a loving and caring world.Though individually a small step, collectively a big change! We need customised platforms and applications, which could bring in automation and AI, allowing dispute resolution process by negotiation, mediation and arbitration available to people in their smart phones and helping mediators and arbitrators to do mediation and arbitration with automated AI-assistance to make minimal errors and with high efficiency. The future of digital revolution is notoriously difficult to predict. Many technological dreams that were once in science fiction are now a reality. Read More

This paternalistic encroachment has led to a power tussle, where courts stake their claims over disputes regardless of the arbitration agreement, as seen in the developments in India. Read More

Creative legal journalism and activist statesmanship for judicial reform cannot be jeopardised by an undefined apprehension of contempt action.
